
TY  - JOUR
T1  - How the Basis for Status Perceptions Varies with Perceiver Status
AU  - Tan, David
AU  - Rider, Christopher I.
Y1  - 2022/03/14
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2023/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.2022.1582
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.2022.1582
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 509
EP  - 531
VL  - 34
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We posit a novel mechanism?socially endogenous calibration?whereby the tendency to align with others? perceptions of organizational status varies systematically with the status of a perceiver?s own organization. We specifically theorize that members of higher-status organizations perceive larger and more correlated status differences among other organizations than members of lower-status organizations do. Using a simulation, we demonstrate how socially endogenous calibration yields these predictions even when quality is uniform across organizations. We further present empirical support for our arguments by analyzing data on individual-level prestige ratings of U.S. law firms. Integrating socially endogenous calibration with prevailing status perspectives based on quality uncertainty, we conclude by elaborating a novel research agenda on stability and instability in organizational status hierarchies.
AB  - We posit a novel mechanism?socially endogenous calibration?whereby the tendency to align with others? perceptions of organizational status varies systematically with the status of a perceiver?s own organization. We specifically theorize that members of higher-status organizations perceive larger and more correlated status differences among other organizations than members of lower-status organizations do. Using a simulation, we demonstrate how socially endogenous calibration yields these predictions even when quality is uniform across organizations. We further present empirical support for our arguments by analyzing data on individual-level prestige ratings of U.S. law firms. Integrating socially endogenous calibration with prevailing status perspectives based on quality uncertainty, we conclude by elaborating a novel research agenda on stability and instability in organizational status hierarchies.
